Part I - (Ford GoBike System Data)¶

by (Abdulmjeed Adahasi)¶

Introduction¶

This analysis is centered on the data set that includes information about individual rides made \ in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco

Table Of Contents¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

| Univariate Exploration ¶

  • What is the average time a rider spends on a bike?
  • what Distribution of the number of trips by gender ?
  • What is the total number of flights according to the type of members?
  • How many users shared their data ?
  • What is the age distribution on the number of trips?
  • What is the Total trips during the weekday?

|| Bivariate Exploration¶

  • what is the Relationship between duration the trip and Every type of user ?
  • comparison of trips on weekdays vs user type, and member gender?
  • What is the relationship between age and the duration of the trip?
  • What is the distribution of user types and gender

||| Multivariate Exploration ¶

  • Is there a difference in the Mean Trip Duration of the Weekdays with the types of users?
  • Is there a difference in the Mean Trip Duration of the Weekdays with the Member Gender?
  • Is there a difference in the average duration of the trip during the hours of the day with the types of users?
  • Is there a difference in the average duration of the trip during the hours of the day with the types of gender of the users?

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are ( before cleaning 183,412 Row after cleaning 174952 Row ) in the dataset with 16 columns, which are described as follows:
duration_sec : trip duration in seconds \
start_time : The date and time of the start of the trip
end_time : The date and time of the end of the trip
start_station_id : Starting station number
start_station_name : The name of the starting station
start_station_latitude : Latitude number on the map for the starting station
start_station_longitude : Longitude number on the map for the starting station
end_station_id : End station number
end_station_name : End station name
end_station_latitude : Latitude number on the map for the starting station
end_station_longitude : Longitude number on the map for the starting station
bike_id : bike number
user_type : User type Customer or Subscriber
member_birth_year : The year of birth of the user to know his age
member_gender : User gender is 'Male'or 'Female' or 'Other'
bike_share_for_all_trip : Find out if the user shared the trip or not
age : The user's age (created to make the data easier to read) by calculating the age from the member_birth_year column


Note: These columns 'start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude', 'member_birth_year' have been drop because they do not serve this research**

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in knowing the difference between gender and age compared to the number of trips, as well as subscriptions, as well as the time of the trip

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the following columns will be useful in the investigation
duration_sec
user_type
member_birth_year
member_gender

#  print the text (proportion) on the bars
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

# Drawing texts are much larger
sb.set(font_scale=1.2)

# remove the grey background 
sb.set_style("white")

sb.countplot(data=df_bike, y='user_type',palette='viridis');

# Logic to print the proportion text on the bars
for i in range (type_counts.shape[0]):
    count = type_counts[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    pct_string ='{:0.01f}%'.format(100*count /df_bike_user_type);
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
    plt.margins(0.10, 0.1);
    plt.text( count+1, i,  pct_string, va='top',   fontsize=15 );
    
plt.xlabel("trips",fontsize=15);
plt.ylabel("",fontsize=12);

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I have an interest in the duration of the trip and whether it is affected by the type of user or the gender of the user during the days of the week or hours of the day.\ \ The results during the weekdays were: The average trip duration during Saturdays, Sundays, and Mondays for customers increased significantly, in contrast to the participants, the increase was very slight.\ \ And when comparing the days of the week with the gender of the users: there is an increase in the duration of the trip during Thursdays, Saturdays, and Sundays (non-specified) compared to males and females.\ \ For the results, compare the duration of the trip during the hours of the day with the type of user: There is a significant increase in the duration of the trip for customers between one hour and four hours compared to subscribers.\ \ And when compared to the gender of the user: There is a significant increase in the duration of the trip during the period from one hour to four hours. The duration of the trip increases significantly among women and (unspecified gender) compared to males.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

There are interesting results, which is an increase in the duration of the trips between one hour and four o’clock compared to the type of users. Customers have a clear increase in the duration of the trip compared to subscribers in the duration of the trip. And when compared to the gender of the users, women and (non-specified) have an increase in the duration of the trip compared to males

Conclusions¶

Through the above research, we notice in general that the majority of users are male, and we also note that subscribers are more than customers\ We have noticed that with age, the duration of the trip decreases\ Saturday, Sunday, and Monday have been considered the most increase in the duration of the trip between the days of the week for customers compared to other days.\ And when comparing the duration of the trip during the hours of the day, we find that from one o'clock to four o'clock the duration of the trip is longer, with a big difference for customers, as well as women and (gender not specified)\ Conclusion: The duration of the trip for customers is more than the duration of the trip for subscribers, \ and the duration of the trip from 1 to 4 o'clock is more than the average duration during the hours of the day
